31
00:01:59,250 --> 00:02:04,200
Most fuels contain hydrogen, which forms water
when burned, and the heating value of a fuel

32
00:02:04,200 --> 00:02:08,030
will be different depending on whether the
water in combustion products is in liquid

33
00:02:08,030 --> 00:02:09,449
or vapor form.

34
00:02:09,449 --> 00:02:14,530
The heating value is called “lower heating
value”, or LHV, when the water in the combustion

35
00:02:14,530 --> 00:02:20,220
gases is a vapor, and “higher heating value”,
or HHV, when the water in the combustion gases

36
00:02:20,220 --> 00:02:27,230
is completely condensed, and thus the heat
of vaporization is also recovered.

37
00:02:27,230 --> 00:02:32,750
The LHV is often used as the measure of energy
per kg of fuel supplied to the gas or gas

38
00:02:32,750 --> 00:02:37,300
turbine engine because the exhaust gases have
such a high temperature that the water formed

39
00:02:37,300 --> 00:02:43,940
is a vapor as it leaves the engine with other
combustion products.

40
00:02:43,940 --> 00:02:48,900
The HHV is often used as the measure of energy
per kilogram of fuel supplied to the steam

41
00:02:48,900 --> 00:02:53,659
power cycle because there are heat transfer
processes within the cycle that absorb enough

42
00:02:53,659 --> 00:02:58,019
energy from the products of combustion that
some of the water vapor formed during combustion

43
